[[Image:LDS Church presence 2007.png|thumb|400px|right|{{legend|#336699|Countries and territories with at least one LDS temple}} {{legend|#99CCFF|Countries and territories with no LDS temple, but with organized congregations and missionaries}} {{legend|#CCCCCC|Countries and territories with no official LDS presence}}]]
'''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''', widely known as the '''LDS Church''' or the '''Mormon Church''', is a religious organization originating from the [[Latter Day Saint movement]] founded by [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]  It is the largest and most well-known [[Religious denomination|denomination]] of this movement. The church is headquartered in [[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]] and has established congregations and [[Temple (Latter Day Saints)|temples]] worldwide, reporting approximately 13 million members on its rolls.<ref name = SLT13>"LDS Church says membership now 13 million worldwide", ''Salt Lake Tribune'', June 25, 2007.</ref><ref name = LDS13>Press Release, LDS Church, [http://www.lds.org/ldsnewsroom/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=80fc110c00c53110VgnVCM100000176f620aRCRD&vgnextchannel=9ae411154963d010VgnVCM1000004e94610aRCRD "One Million Missionaries, Thirteen Million Members"], 25 June 2007.</ref>

Adherents, usually referred to as ''[[Latter-day Saint]]s'', ''LDS'', or ''[[Mormon]]s'', believe that [[Jesus Christ]] leads the church through [[revelation]] given to the [[President of the Church]], who is considered to be a [[Prophet, seer, and revelator|prophet]]. They believe Jesus Christ is the Son of God, was born of a virgin, lived a perfect and sinless life, was crucified, and through his atoning sacrifice mankind can be forgiven of their sins. They believe Jesus was resurrected on the third day and currently sits on the right hand of God the Father. Though these are fundamental Christian beliefs, Latter-day Saints do not consider themselves part of the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]], or [[Protestantism|Protestant]] traditions.

The church teaches that it is a [[Restoration (Latter Day Saints)|restoration]] of the church instituted by Jesus Christ. It teaches that before Joseph Smith restored the true church, an [[Great Apostasy|apostasy]] occurred shortly after the death of [[Saint Peter|Peter]] and the other original [[Twelve apostles|apostles]]. The church teaches that Christian denominations created during this period deviated from Christ's original teachings, and that they operated without Christ's divinely appointed authority. Latter-day Saints believe in the divine authority of the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]] and also have additional [[book]]s in their [[Biblical canon|scriptural canon]]: the ''[[Book of Mormon]]'', the ''[[Doctrine and Covenants]]'', and the ''[[Pearl of Great Price (Latter Day Saints)|Pearl of Great Price]]''.

Historically, the church has distinguished itself from other Christian denominations by its practice of temple [[Ordinance (Latter Day Saints)|ordinances]] such as [[baptism for the dead]] and the [[Endowment (Latter Day Saints)|Endowment]], its doctrinal views on the [[Godhead (Latter Day Saints)|Godhead]], and its former practice of [[plural marriage]].<ref>See {{lds|D&C|dc|132}}. The church has since abandoned the practice of plural marriage.</ref> The church teaches that it is "the only true and living church upon the face of the whole earth",<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|1|30}}</ref> but it has cooperated with other religious organizations in promoting humanitarian and moral causes.

== History ==
{{main|History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints}}
{{seealso|Category:History of the Latter Day Saint movement}}
{{Latter Day Saint movement}}
[[Image:Joseph Smith Jr bronze bust Conference Center.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bust of [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]]]
The LDS Church is the largest of the denominations from the [[Latter Day Saint movement]] that claim to be a continuation of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Christ]], founded by [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]] on [[April 6]] [[1830]] in [[New York]].<!--

FOOTNOTE--><ref>The majority of witnesses say the church was organized [[April 6]] [[1830]] in the log home of [[Joseph Smith, Sr.]] in the [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]] area, followed by a meeting the next Sunday in nearby [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]] at the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] Nevertheless, one of Smith's histories and a later reminiscence by [[David Whitmer]] say the church was organized at the Whitmer home in Fayette. See [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)]]. The church refers to Fayette as the place of organization in all its official [[publication]]s.</ref><!--

--> Joseph Smith legally established this early church soon after publishing the ''[[Book of Mormon]]''. The church rapidly gained a large following of individuals that viewed Smith as their [[prophet]]. The growth of Smith's following was attributed by some to the convincing power of the Book of Mormon, which Smith said he translated from a book of [[golden plates]] that were buried near his home in a place shown to him by an [[Moroni (prophet)|angel]].<ref name="JSTestimony">[http://lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=69f9307e3584b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 Joseph Smith's Testimony]</ref>

In late 1830, Smith envisioned a [[Zion (Latter Day Saints)|"city of Zion"]] in [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] lands near [[Independence, Missouri]]. In October 1830 he sent his second-in-command [[Oliver Cowdery]] and others on a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|mission]] to the area.<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|32}}</ref> Passing through [[Kirtland, Ohio]], the missionaries converted a congregation of [[Disciples of Christ]] led by [[Sidney Rigdon]], and in 1831, Smith decided to temporarily move his followers to Kirtland until the [[Missouri]] area could be colonized. The church headquarters remained in Kirtland from 1831 to 1838; meanwhile, the church built [[Kirtland Temple|its first temple]] and continued to grow.

On [[July 20]], [[1831]] Smith circulated a written revelation that [[Independence, Missouri]] was to be the center place for the city of Zion.<ref>{{lds|D&C|dc|57|1-3}}</ref> Though many of Smith's followers attempted to colonize Missouri throughout the 1830s and Smith himself moved there in 1838, the church faced political and military opposition from other Missouri settlers. After a series of raids on Mormon settlements, the church formed its own militia to defend its members and the [[Mormon War]] of 1838 ensued, culminating in the religion being expelled from the state under an [[Extermination Order]] signed by [[Lilburn W. Boggs|the governor of Missouri]]. The church then established its new headquarters in [[Nauvoo, Illinois]], a city they built on drained swampland by the [[Mississippi River]], where Smith served as mayor. There, the church built a [[Nauvoo Temple|new temple]], and thrived until Smith and his brother [[Hyrum Smith|Hyrum]], who was serving as [[Assistant President of the Church|assistant president]] and [[Presiding Patriarch|patriarch of the church]], were [[death of Joseph Smith, Jr.|killed by a mob]] in 1844. The Smith brothers were awaiting trial after the Nauvoo city council decided to destroy a [[Nauvoo Expositor|local newspaper]] that accused Smith of practicing a form of [[polygamy]] and intending to establish himself as a [[Theocracy|theocratic]] king. Specific threats against the leadership of the church and violent action against its members were also made. While the legality of destroying a printing press that published violent threats against a community in 1844 is even today uncertain,<ref>For a discussion, see [[Dallin H. Oaks]]. "The Suppression of the Nauvoo Expositor." ''Utah Law Review'' '''9''' (Winter 1965):862–903. Oaks was not an LDS Apostle when he wrote this opinion.</ref> Hyrum and Joseph were nevertheless promptly charged with disruption of the peace and high treason. Joseph Smith, at the time, was a minor candidate for [[President of the United States]] with [[Sidney Rigdon]] as his running mate.

[[Image:Slc mormon tempel.jpg|thumb|right|235px|The [[Salt Lake Temple]] of '''The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''' is the largest attraction in the city's [[Temple Square]].]]

After the murder of the Smiths, a [[succession crisis]] ensued whereby a number of church leaders campaigned to lead the church. The majority of adherents voted to accept the succession claims presented by the [[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles]], led by [[Brigham Young]]. Their claim was based on a March 1844 meeting wherein Joseph committed the "keys of the kingdom" on the twelve apostles with Young as their [[President of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles|leader]]. After continued difficulties and persecution in Illinois, Young left Nauvoo in 1846 and led [[Mormon pioneers|his followers]] to what later became the state of [[Utah]] (then part of [[Mexico]]), and began to colonize the area with numerous communities.

Young incorporated The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints as a legal entity under the laws of the [[Territory of Utah]]. He initially governed his followers as a [[theocracy|theocratic]] leader serving in both political and religious positions. He openly encouraged the practice of [[plural marriage]]. When this practice became known in [[Washington, D.C.]], the United States sent federal troops there in 1857, [[Utah War|deposed Young]], and replaced him with [[Alfred Cumming (governor)|a non-Mormon territorial governor]], though Young still wielded significant political power as [[President of the Church]]. Young was followed by other powerful leaders, who defiantly followed the dictates of their personal beliefs in the face of U.S. efforts to outlaw Mormon polygamous marriages. Political and legal wrangling over the polygamy issue escalated until 1890, when church president [[Wilford Woodruff]] issued a [[1890 Manifesto|Manifesto]] that officially suspended the practice.<ref>{{lds|Official Declaration —|od|1}}</ref> Relations with the United States markedly improved after 1890, and especially after 1904, when church president [[Joseph F. Smith]] [[Reed Smoot hearings|disavowed polygamy]] before the [[United States Congress]] and issued a "[[Second Manifesto]]" calling for all polygamous marriages in the church to cease. Since this time, the church has adopted a policy of [[excommunication|excommunicating]] its members found practicing polygamy. In 1998, President Gordon B. Hinckley stated, <blockquote>
"If any of our members are found to be practicing plural marriage, they are excommunicated, the most serious penalty the Church can impose. Not only are those so involved in direct violation of the civil law, they are in violation of the law of this Church."<ref>[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=7c86605ff590c010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 Gordon B. Hinckley, "What Are People Asking About Us?"] Ensign, November 1998, 70</ref>
</blockquote>

During the [[20th century|twentieth century]], the church experienced a period of strong growth resulting from both a high birth rate and extensive [[proselytism]]. Since the 1990s, the church's growth rate has moderated, but the church continues to gain approximately 300,000 new members annually.{{Fact|date=August 2007}} 

The church has played, at times, a prominent role in political matters, including opposition to [[LGM-118A Peacekeeper|MX Peacekeeper missile]] bases in Utah and [[Nevada]],<ref>“[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=b0d6fc3157a6b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 First Presidency Statement on Basing of MX Missile]”, ''Ensign'', June 1981, 76.</ref> opposing the [[Equal Rights Amendment]],<ref>[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=f8a4615b01a6b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 “The Church and the Proposed Equal Rights Amendment: A Moral Issue”], ''Ensign'', March 1980, insert.</ref> opposing legalized [[gambling]],<ref>[http://www.lds.org/portal/site/LDSOrg/menuitem.b12f9d18fae655bb69095bd3e44916a0/?vgnextoid=2354fccf2b7db010VgnVCM1000004d82620aRCRD&locale=0&sourceId=4ace94bf3938b010VgnVCM1000004d82620a____&hideNav=1 “Church’s Stand against Gambling]”, ''Ensign'', March 1992, 74.</ref> support of bans on [[same-sex marriage]],<!--

FOOTNOTE--><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Same-Gender Attraction
  | publisher = Newsroom.lds.org
  | date = 26 May 2005
  | url = http://www.lds.org/ldsnewsroom/v/index.jsp?vgnextoid=27f71f1dd189f010VgnVCM100000176f620aRCRD&vgnextchannel=726511154963d010VgnVCM1000004e94610aRCRD
